
[1]preceptive

   PRECEP'TIVE, a. [L. proeceptivus.] Giving precepts or commands for the
   regulation of moral conduct; containing precepts; as the preceptive
   parts of the Scriptures.

   1. Directing in moral conduct; giving rules or directions; didactic.

   The lesson given us here is preceptive to us.

   Preceptive poetry.
